---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How often should I clean solar panels in Pakenham?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "For most Pakenham homes the right interval is every 12-18 months. On houses with overhanging gums, paperbarks or close-by livestock paddocks (common on the Pakenham Upper and rural-edge blocks) we drop that to 6-9 months because bird droppings and tree sap don't rinse off in normal rain. Newer estates with clean tile roofs and minimal tree cover - Cardinia Lakes, Lakeside core - generally hold 18 months without significant output loss. We monitor your inverter's daily yield curve as the deciding signal: a 8-12% drop from last summer's baseline is the trigger." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Why do solar panels lose output between cleans in this climate zone?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Pakenham sits on the dust-belt edge of Melbourne's south-east, with strong westerlies pushing fine dust off agricultural land all summer and pollen from gums and grasses for half the year. The dust forms a thin film that natural rain rinses partially but never fully - by month 10 you've typically got an 8-12% transmission loss across the array. Bird droppings, in particular, bake on hard in summer heat and create permanent hot-spots if left for a season; that's a worse problem than dust because it causes localised cell damage, not just transmission loss." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do you use water-fed poles or get on the roof?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Both, depending on roof access and pitch. On single-storey tile roofs at standard 22-degree pitch we'll usually access from a ladder with fall-protection and a soft brush, then rinse with deionised water. On double-storey or steep-pitch roofs (anything above 30 degrees) we use a telescopic water-fed pole from the ground - safer for us and avoids any tile-walking risk. We never use abrasive brushes, never use detergents or soaps, and never use mains pressure on glass - high-pressure water can force its way past the panel frame seal." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Will cleaning void my panel warranty?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Professional cleaning by a CEC-accredited installer using the manufacturer's recommended method (soft brush, deionised or rainwater, no detergent, no high pressure) does not void the warranty - in fact most Tier-1 panel manufacturers (Trina, Jinko, REC, LG) explicitly require regular cleaning as a condition of the 25-year performance warranty. DIY cleaning with the wrong technique can void it: pressure washers, abrasive scourers, glass cleaners with ammonia, or walking on the panel surface all create grounds for a warranty rejection. We document each clean with before/after photos so you have an audit trail." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What does a Pakenham solar panel clean cost?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "A standard single-storey 6.6kW system (around 18-20 panels) is typically $180-$240 plus GST including a soft-brush + deionised water clean, a visual array inspection, and an inverter health check. A 10kW or larger system on a double-storey runs $280-$380. We give a fixed price upfront based on system size, panel count and roof access - no surprises. If we find a fault during the inspection (cracked panel, failed MC4 connector, loose mounting bracket) we'll quote any remedial work separately rather than tacking it on." }
    }
  ]
};
---
<Layout
  title="Solar Panel Cleaning Pakenham | Output Restored | (03) 9003 0108"
  description="Why dust-belt Pakenham panels lose 8-12% output between cleans, the wet-vs-dry method, soft-brush vs soft-soap-rinse, and the 18-month vs 6-month interval depending on tree cover."
  canonical="https://pakenhamsolarbattery.com.au/panel-cleaning-pakenham/">
  <Fragment slot="head">
    <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(faqSchema)} />
  </Fragment>

  <section class="hero">
    <div class="hero-inner">
      <span class="hero-eyebrow">Service &amp; maintenance</span>
      <h1>Solar panel cleaning in <span class="accent">Pakenham &amp; Cardinia</span>.</h1>
      <p class="hero-sub">
        Dust-belt Pakenham panels typically lose 8-12 percent output between cleans.
        Here's how often to actually clean them, the soft-brush + deionised water method
        that doesn't void warranty, and how tree cover changes the interval from 18
        months to 6.
      </p>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a class="btn btn-primary" href="tel:+61390030108">&#9742; Call (03) 9003 0108</a>
        <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/quote/">Book a panel clean</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <h2>Why your panels are losing output you can't see.</h2>
      <div style="max-width: 65rem;">
        <p>
          When a solar panel is brand new and clean, the front glass transmits more than
          93 percent of incoming sunlight to the silicon cells underneath. Twelve months
          later, after a Pakenham summer of westerly dust off the cropping country, a
          Pakenham winter of leaf litter and bird traffic, and a spring of pollen storms,
          that transmission has typically dropped to 82-85 percent. The panel hasn't
          aged - the glass is just covered in a thin opaque film that rain doesn't
          rinse fully because it dries onto the surface between showers.
        </p>
        <p>
          You can see it on the inverter app if you know where to look. Compare a clear
          November Sunday from this year against the same Sunday last year. The peak-hour
          generation should be within 2 percent (panels degrade about 0.5 percent per
          year, so a brand-new 6.6kW system should still be at 6.3kW peak after 6 years).
          If you're at 5.8kW where you should be at 6.3kW, that 8 percent gap is dirt.
          That's roughly $200-$320 a year in lost generation on a typical Pakenham bill -
          easily more than the cost of a clean.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">The two things that matter most.</h3>
        <p>
          The dust film is the slow background killer. The faster, sharper killer is
          <strong>bird droppings</strong>, particularly from magpies and cockies that
          favour roof ridges. A single 50mm dropping that sits on a panel for a Pakenham
          summer doesn't just cover three cells - it causes them to heat to a hot-spot
          while the rest of the string keeps producing, eventually damaging the cell
          permanently. After 18 months untreated, that's no longer a cleaning job; it's
          a panel replacement. We see this every summer.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section section-alt">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <h2>How we actually clean: wet brush, not pressure spray.</h2>
      <div style="max-width: 65rem;">
        <p>
          The right method is the one every Tier-1 manufacturer specifies in their
          warranty fine print: <strong>soft natural-bristle brush, deionised or
          rainwater, no detergent, no abrasive, no high pressure, no walking on the panel
          face</strong>. That's it. Every other method risks scratching the
          anti-reflective coating on the glass, forcing water past the EVA seal at the
          frame, or voiding the 25-year performance warranty outright.
        </p>
        <p>
          For single-storey tile roofs with safe access, we'll set up roof-edge protection,
          climb on, work each panel with a 250mm soft-bristle brush dipped in a deionised
          water reservoir, and rinse with the same water. Deionised water is the secret -
          mains tap water from Pakenham leaves a calcium spotting as it evaporates that
          looks streaky and traps more dust the following week. Deionised water dries
          completely clear. For double-storey or steep-pitched roofs we use a
          <strong>water-fed telescopic pole</strong> from the ground, same brush head,
          same water - keeps us off slippery tiles and is just as effective.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">What's NOT a panel clean.</h3>
        <p>
          A pressure washer is not a panel clean - the impact pressure of a 1500-PSI
          jet exceeds the panel frame seal rating and forces water into the laminate.
          Window cleaner with ammonia is not a panel clean - it strips the
          anti-reflective coating. A garden hose on full pressure with a kitchen sponge
          is not a panel clean - the abrasive side of the sponge micro-scratches the
          glass. A magic eraser is not a panel clean - it's an abrasive masquerading as
          a non-abrasive. We get warranty-claim phone calls every season from people
          who've tried these and now have a documented "improper maintenance" finding
          on their array.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <h2>The right interval by suburb and tree cover.</h2>
      <div style="max-width: 65rem;">
        <p>
          One interval doesn't fit every Pakenham roof. Here's the rough guide we use
          when scheduling annual maintenance:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>18 months</strong> - newer estates with tile roofs, minimal tree
            cover, no livestock paddock within 500m. Most of Cardinia Lakes, Lakeside,
            Heritage Springs core.</li>
          <li><strong>12 months</strong> - the default for most Pakenham, Officer and
            Beaconsfield homes with one or two trees within dropping range.</li>
          <li><strong>9 months</strong> - Pakenham Upper and Cardinia rural-edge blocks
            with significant gum cover, paperbarks or livestock nearby.</li>
          <li><strong>6 months</strong> - homes directly under or alongside mature eucalypts,
            or coastal-influenced sites where salt-spray gets airborne in storms.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          On every visit we also do a <strong>visual array inspection</strong>: check for
          micro-cracks (we look for the cell pattern under raking light), inspect MC4
          connectors and DC isolators for water ingress (a notorious failure on 10+yr
          installs), check the mounting brackets and rail bolts, and confirm the
          inverter's recent generation curves look healthy. We send through a one-page
          report with before/after photos and any flagged items.
        </p>
        <p>
          The honest answer for most Pakenham customers is: book a clean every spring,
          ahead of the summer generation peak. That single visit catches dirt before it
          costs you the highest-yield months of the year, and the visual inspection
          catches connector or panel faults before they grow into warranty claims.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section section-cta">
    <div class="section-inner" style="text-align:center;">
      <h2>Book a Pakenham panel clean before summer peak.</h2>
      <p style="max-width: 50rem; margin: 0 auto 2rem;">
        Fixed price upfront based on your system size and roof access, soft-brush method,
        deionised water, written inspection report. CEC-accredited installer, fully
        insured for roof work.
      </p>
      <div class="hero-actions" style="justify-content:center;">
        <a class="btn btn-primary" href="tel:+61390030108">&#9742; Call (03) 9003 0108</a>
        <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="mailto:quotes@pakenhamsolarbattery.com.au">Email quotes@pakenhamsolarbattery.com.au</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
